Aside from the typo, the calculation of the uppercase letters is incorrect.

First, there&#39;s no need to create `ch` array, copy the characters from the input string, and then check the chars in `ch` array.

Second, an assumption that the uppercase letters reside in the range `[65, 90]` is applicable only to English letters.  There are several `Character::isUpperCase` methods to check if a [character](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/lang/Character.html#isUpperCase-char-) or a [Unicode codepoint](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/lang/Character.html#isUpperCase-int-) is upper case.  `Character::isUpperCase(char c)` has been existing for a while since Java 1.0.

So, that being said, an example counting uppercase letters could be as follows:
```java
public static int numUpperCase(String s) {
    int num = 0;
    if (s != null) {
        for (char c : s.toCharArray()) {
            if (Character.isUpperCase(c)) num++;
        }
    }
    return num;
}
```
A oneliner using Stream API:
```java
static int numUpperCase(String str) {
    return Optional.ofNullable(str)
           .map(s -&gt; (int) s.chars().filter(Character::isUpperCase).count())
           .orElse(0); // if input string is null
}
```

